Observation Details: Interesting story. On 1 November Wayne Weber reported  One but didn’t give a specific location at Tulalip bay. I was out of town. Today I refound 2  at a location I don’t check very often, A pullout at hermosa,bayside. When I stopped I heard a scrub jay across the street behind a yellow house. 7810, the Murphy’s.! Then I saw one and it responded to playback. Shortly there were 2. The last time I saw a scrub jay at Tulalip  Was 2011 .one stayed for  winter and  Came to our feeder with r tStellers jays. So thank you Wayne. Photos

Media notes: California Scrub-Jay

Observation Details: Two birds in this sagebrush corral. Both were bright blue above, bright white below, UTC look white in pictures, bills seemed beefy enough (but there's considerable overlap in the two species with regard to bill shape, but combined with the bright blue look of these, the fairly thick bills help). Necklace good on sides, but maybe so-so for CASJ overall. And they perched in the open! I consider that a field mark too. This location is along the road, near the 7.0 mile marker (as in 7 miles from Mono Co.!), and about 3 miles east of Sweetwater Summit. Well east of Nye Canyon and where California SJ's are thought to fade out. I had been photographing scrub-jays this day from TRE east. I'm about to enter some other older scrub jay records from Lyon Co. as Woodhouse or slash (woodhouse/California), I think these were "solid" California, as seen in pictures (though this region is a blend zone where genes are mixed and 'tweeners are frequent and any bird regardless of morphological appearance could have mixed genes)

stakeout California Scrub-Jay, Yuma--S Hettema St (2016)
Observation Details: Potentially first state record. Discovered by & in back yard of Margaret Kunes end of August then disappeared or unseen until few days ago. Thanks to Chris McCreedy, local eBird reviewer for bringing it to the community's attention that this was a California and not a Woodhouse's. First arrived this morning at 07:08, perched in top of tree across street (to west) before visiting feeding area. Landed in tree above feeders then worked its way down to peanut feeder & then ground (where most of the peanuts were). Disappeared in foliage with peanut. Returned less than ten minutes later . Apparently process repeated several times over the course of the morning. Comparing to personally more familiar Woodhouse's Scrub-Jay, this individual appeared to be deeper/darker blue overall; more distinct white eyebrow, black mask, white bib; dark blue nearly framed the bib missing only in the bottom center; white undertail coverts otherwise pale gray underparts.
Looks like a Coastal form by bright coloration and extent of blue collar.  Very far inland. Woodhouse's is more muted and the demarcations are less distinct.

Observation Details: This Scrub-Jay was found near the small city park on the highway in Brogan. We had some questions about this Scrub-Jay: California or Woodhouse's? When first seen, it appeared to be paler than the Willamette Valley California Scrub-Jays that we see often. The breast band appeared paler, also. However, Woodhouse's illustrations show a a more dingy or grayer breast than California. This bird appears fairly light on the breast- although the photo lighting could change this. The overall blue coloring may be too bright on this bird for a Woodhouse's. Along with some other characteristics, this bird appears to be a California. These photos have been cropped, no other editing done.

It was perched up my fence looking around. After being on the fence for a minute or two, it went down to the ground to start foraging. It didn't seem to have found anything and flew away. I wanted to see it again so I waited until it came to my front yard. Once again, it didn't find anything of use and left to the house across the street where it did end up taking dead plants and twigs.
